<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in a Bottom-Watering Tray</h2>

  <h3>1. Proper Fit with Seed Trays</h3>
  <p>
    The tray should match the size of your seed-starting inserts. A poor fit leads to uneven watering and wasted space.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Enough Depth to Hold Water</h3>
  <p>
    A tray needs enough depth to allow water to soak into the cells without immediately running dry.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Durability</h3>
  <p>
    Thin trays can crack or warp, especially when repeatedly filled and drained. A sturdier tray is usually a better long-term investment.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Leak Resistance</h3>
  <p>
    Indoor setups depend on clean watering. A tray that leaks or flexes too much can create mess quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Ease of Handling</h3>
  <p>
    Trays should be easy to lift, move, and empty without spilling water across your setup.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Tray Depth Matters</h2>

  <p>
    One of the most common issues with bottom watering is using trays that are too shallow. Shallow trays do not hold enough water to allow proper absorption, which leads to uneven moisture levels.
  </p>

  <p>
    A slightly deeper tray gives you more control and reduces the need for constant refilling during watering.
  </p>

  <p>
    For many gardeners, choosing a tray with more depth improves consistency immediately.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Full Systems vs Simple Trays</h2>

  <h3>Simple Trays</h3>
  <p>
    These are often the best choice for most gardeners. They are easy to use, flexible, and compatible with many seed-starting inserts.
  </p>

  <h3>Integrated Systems</h3>
  <p>
    Some setups combine trays, inserts, and domes into one system. These can work well, but they are usually less flexible if you want to change tray types later.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most home setups, simple trays paired with standard inserts provide the most flexibility.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overlook</h2>

  <p>
    Bottom watering works best when trays are not overcrowded. If too many inserts are packed into one tray, water distribution can become uneven.
  </p>

  <p>
    Another common issue is not allowing enough time for absorption. Good trays help, but the watering process still needs time to work properly.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/when-to-water-seedlings/">when to water seedlings</a>.
  </p>
</section>

